<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-667-484  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 667 484.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Sept 18 1989 v6 n37 p1(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Manufacturers automate to fight foreign challenge.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Breidenbach, Susan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>US manufacturers, including Rockwell, Xerox and Boeing are turningto automation to help cut costs and fight foreign competition.andO;Allen-Bradley, a subsidiary of Rockwell International thatmanufactures automation and control systems convened a task forceto decide whether or not computer-integrated manufacturing (CIM)would save its motor contact business.andP;  The task force decided aCIM operation could produce competitive products if it wascompletely paperless and people-less.andP;  The typical 110 dayinventory would be reduced to zero for a $15 to $20 million pricetag.andP;  The company says it was money well-spent.andP;  Reject rates werereduced from 3.5 percent of sales to 115 parts per million.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Boeing Aerospace Co. (automation)Xerox Corp. (automation).andO;Ticker:    XRX.andO;Topic:     AutomationForeign CompetitionComputer-Aided DesignComputer-Integrated ManufacturingIntegrated Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>